en":{"1256–about 1315":"1256–about 1315","1246–1315":"1246–1315","1274–1320":"1274–1320","1278–Male":"1278–Deceased","1282–Male":"1282–Deceased","1284–Male":"1284–Deceased","1256–1315":"1256–1315","1274":"1274","1273":"1273","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","liv 1315":"1315","1290":"1290","ABT 1282":"about 1282","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1246":"1246","1256":"1256","1278":"1278","about 1315":"about 1315","1320":"1320","about 1274":"about 1274","1317":"1317","Seaborough, Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Of Sampit, Dorcet,":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Seaborough, Somerset, England":"Seaborough, Somerset, England","of Seaborough, Somerset, Eng.":"Seaborough, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Seaborough, Dorset, England":"Seaborough, Dorset, England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":3,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":34,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":59,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda was born in 1256, in Seaborough, Dorset, England. She married Elias Gould in 1273, in Seaborough, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died about 1315, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1256–about 1315":"1256–umbes 1315","1246–1315":"1246–1315","1274–1320":"1274–1320","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1256–1315":"1256–1315","1274":"1274","1273":"1273","1284":"1284","1282":"1282","liv 1315":"1315","1290":"1290","ABT 1282":"umbes 1282","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1246":"1246","1256":"1256","1